His notes are in German, and Ι suppose this is the reason ‘why Ruperti's edition continues to be much used by studente in this country. It is the work of an industrious man of weak mind, always liable to waver when his judgment happens to be right, but never to be relied upon in cases of difficulty. Nor is he strictly honest, for he changed his interpre- tations in some instances in his later edition, without acknowledging , that he was indebted to Heinrich for his second thoughts.
